data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compiled and ran without issues:

```csharp
Span<nint>  nints  = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

The native-sized integers (`nint`/`nuint`, introduced in C# 9) are unmanaged types, so they satisfy the constraint required by `stackalloc`. On this 64-bit system, `nint.MaxValue` was `9223372036854775807` (i.e., `long.MaxValue`), confirming 8-byte native pointers.
